# **Increase R\&D Productivity** {#increase-r&d-productivity}

**Industry Context**  
Despite tremendous growth in R\&D investments, success rates of new drugs have remained flat over the last two decades. Time-to-market for approved drugs averages 12+ years and $2B+ in spend. Even for successful drug candidates, delays in launch erode lifetime revenues that sustain top-line growth. 

**Business Challenges / Urgency**

* Drug development has become more specialized, focusing more on biology than chemistry, and targeting narrower patient populations (eg., patients with specific gene expressions).   
* As drugs and clinical trials become more complex and targeted, more trials struggle to meet patient recruitment targets, particularly in diverse patient populations.  
* Delayed trials and increasing regulatory scrutiny result in fewer broad approvals and less time on market (before patent expiration), decreasing the overall return on capital.

**Technical Challenges**

* **Complex Life Sciences Data and Applications**: Data silos, domain specific file formats, and a wide range of advanced analytics methods makes it difficult to integrate and interpret information effectively.  
* **Disconnected Tools & Teams**: Unlocking R\&D requires different personas that have their own tools and skill sets: It is a challenge for many organizations to easily access, govern, and collaborate on data.  
* **Reproducibility**: Research (and ultimately regulatory approvals) require robust data lineage that supports reproducibility. 

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI supports pre-training multi-omics models (like geneformer models) & agent frameworks for research assistants  
* **Governance:** Unity Catalog supports lineage for regulatory submissions; Volumes enables integration of complex data assets  
* **Streaming & ETL:** Lakehouse Monitoring enables AI-assisted quality assurance of clinical data  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** DBSQL unlocks efficient analysis and dashboarding of both research and clinical trial data (egs., chromatography insights, clinical trial status)  
* **Data Collaboration:** Clean Rooms support secure data collaboration, for example, across clinical trial sponsors, sites, and IRBs

Accelerated drug target identification: reduced the time it takes data scientists and computational biologists to run queries on their entire dataset from 30 minutes to down 3 seconds – 600x improvement\! **Customer Story, AstraZeneca:**

| \>\> Challenge AstraZeneca discovers, develops, and commercializes groundbreaking drugs for some of the world’s most serious diseases. The biggest obstacle to new innovations is the inability to tap into all of the scientific information available to them faster than the pace of new data coming in. They needed a platform that enabled them to build scalable, performant data pipelines that feed machine learning models designed to help their scientists make targeted decisions.  Their scientists were unable to quickly make informed decisions with all of the available scientific information at their fingertips. They struggled with data residing in disjointed sources both within the company as well as external public databases. Furthermore, as new scientific research continues to be released at a rapid pace, it became virtually impossible to keep up-to-date with the pace of scientific discovery. Infrastructure complexity: Finding the infrastructure that allowed for flexibility but didn’t require constant maintenance. Massive volumes of disjointed data: Tasked with ingesting, parsing, and analyzing millions of data points across 100s of data sources including internal data sources and public sources including technical literature, public databases, etc. Struggled to scale operations to support data science efforts with open source Python notebooks. \>\> Databricks Solution With Databricks, they are able to leverage data and machine learning to build a recommendation engine that empowers scientists to more easily uncover new novel drugs quicker, cheaper and more effectively.AstraZeneca leverages the Databricks Data Intelligence Platform to help build a knowledge graph of biological insights and facts. The graph powers a recommendation system that enables any AstraZeneca scientist to generate novel target hypotheses, for any disease, leveraging all of the data available to them. Fully managed platform: Simplified cluster management and maintenance of analytic resources at scale. Built scale, performant data pipelines: Able to leverage NLP across a huge library of scientific literature and data sources for downstream analysis. Accelerating machine learning innovation: Data scientists are empowered to build and train models that provide ranking predictions that will help them make smarter decisions. \>\> Measurable Impact Since moving to Databricks, AstraZeneca is now able to more easily process millions of data points from thousands of sources. Removing the barriers of scale has allowed them to more reliably extract meaningful insights that can result in novel drugs designed to help people live healthier lives. Improved operational efficiency: Features such as cluster management and auto-scaling of clusters has improved operations from data ingest to managing the entire machine learning lifecycle. Better data science productivity: Shared notebook environment with support for multiple languages has improved team productivity. Faster time-to-insight: The recommendation engine powered by Databricks has improved their ability to make more informed hypotheses, allowing them to accelerate time-to-market for novel drugs and medicines. |

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

**Findability:** Data is catalogued with built-in search and discovery

**Interoperability:** Based on open source & open standards; Supports all data modalities

### **Standardization and Interoperability**: [The Databricks lakehouse architecture](https://www.databricks.com/product/data-lakehouse) enables seamless interoperability by integrating unstructured, semi-structured, and structured data from data lakes and data warehouses into a single, unified platform based on open-source technologies such as [Delta Lake](https://delta.io/) and [Unity Catalog](https://www.databricks.com/blog/open-sourcing-unity-catalog). This approach facilitates the integration of diverse datasets, supporting open data formats and interfaces to reduce vendor lock-in and simplify data integration across different systems. By leveraging open-source technologies and providing a centralized data catalog, [Unity Catalog](https://www.databricks.com/product/unity-catalog), Databricks ensures that data is easily discoverable, accessible, and can be integrated with external systems in a compliant and auditable manner. This enables researchers to deliver on the [FAIR principles](https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618) (Findability, Accessibility, Interoperability, and Reusability) for scientific data management, promoting collaboration, reproducibility, and data-driven insights.

### **Regulatory Considerations**: Databricks Unity Catalog enables organizations to meet stringent regulatory requirements, such as HIPAA and GDPR, while enhancing data findability and accessibility. With its centralized metadata repository and [powerful semantic search capabilities](https://www.databricks.com/blog/adding-intelligence-to-databricks-search), users can quickly locate relevant data assets based on context and meaning. The platform's [fine-grained access controls](https://docs.databricks.com/en/security/auth/index.html), [identity federation](https://docs.databricks.com/en/admin/users-groups/index.html), and comprehensive [audit logging](https://docs.databricks.com/en/admin/account-settings/audit-logs.html) ensure data security and compliance. Additionally, Unity Catalog provides advanced metadata management, tagging, and data lineage tracking to enhance the discoverability and reproducibility of experiments. To further ensure regulatory compliance, Databricks offers robust [data encryption](https://docs.databricks.com/en/security/keys/index.html) and [secret management features](https://docs.databricks.com/en/security/secrets/index.html). The platform also integrates open-source technologies, such as the [Delta Sharing Protocol](https://www.databricks.com/blog/2021/05/26/introducing-delta-sharing-an-open-protocol-for-secure-data-sharing.html), which enables secure data sharing between parties. [Databricks Clean Rooms](https://www.databricks.com/product/clean-room) facilitates secure collaboration among researchers from different organizations while meeting data residency requirements. These capabilities collectively enable organizations to uphold strict data protection standards while allowing authorized users to efficiently discover, access, and share necessary data for analysis and research in a secure, compliant environment—even across organizational boundaries.

### **Data Volume and Complexity**: Databricks is built on a scalable cloud infrastructure that can handle the vast and complex datasets typical of omics research. With its integration with Apache Spark and a high-performance compute engine powered by [Photon](https://www.databricks.com/product/photon), Databricks enables cost-effective distributed data processing. Additionally, by having the [ML/AI stack built on top of a powerful data management infrastructure](https://docs.databricks.com/en/machine-learning/index.html), it reduces the friction of managing separate tech stacks for data management and advanced analytics while accelerating time to value.

# **Optimize Supply Chain & Manufacturing** {#optimize-supply-chain-&-manufacturing}

**Industry Context**  
Many Life Sciences organizations have struggled to do real-time reporting on data from ERP systems like SAP, creating gaps in inventory moving through distribution. These gaps can result in unfulfilled orders, financial penalties, lost revenue, and critical shortages ranging from medications to devices at hospitals. Similarly, many organizations have not embraced smart manufacturing to enable them to mitigate production issues & drug shortages.

**Business Challenges / Urgency**

* The COVID-19 pandemic exposed vulnerabilities in global supply chains, particularly in the life sciences sector with prominent examples like cold chain distribution of vaccines. To increase resilience, Life Sciences companies must create end-to-end visibility to diversify suppliers and quickly identify and address disruptions.   
* In parallel, based on advances in drug discovery, new products (eg., CAR-T cell therapy) are becoming more complex to manufacture at scale, resulting in pressure to increase yield to meet demand.

**Technical Challenges** 

* **Diverse Data** (from increasing product complexity): Manufacturing data for biologics and cell therapy is more complex than small molecule products.  
* **Real-Time Visibility:** Many Life Sciences organizations cannot respond to supply chain issues and / or manufacturing in the real-time, impacting key metrics like OTIF (on-time, in-full) and CQAs (critical quality attributes) in manufacturing.   
* **Prescriptive Analytics:** Organizations often are stuck at descriptive reporting, failing to proactively predict and manage inventory, or support initiatives like predictive maintenance.

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI provides a complete suite of ML/AI tools for training & deploying predictive models for applications like anomaly detection & forecasting   
* **Governance:** Unity Catalog tracks entire lineage from ingest through serving, allowing better transparency of models & supporting regulatory needs  
* **Streaming & ETL:** Delta Live Tables offers declarative pipelines to combine batch & streaming from different sources & sensors  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** DBSQL supports reporting & dashboarding for supply chain KPIs like OTIF  
* **Data Collaboration:** Marketplace provides quick access to third party data & models (eg., Accuweather)

# **Improve Commercial Effectiveness** {#improve-commercial-effectiveness}

**Industry Context**  
Life Sciences organizations have many stakeholders: healthcare professionals (HCPs), payers, and patients. Their needs are as diverse as the myriad, disparate sources of data available. Every initiative supporting product commercialization \- from the nudge a patient receives to adopt healthy behaviors, to real world evidence generation for payers, to recommending the next-best action for providers, requires intelligence derived from all available data.

**Business Challenges / Urgency**  
The Life Sciences industry is rapidly evolving in terms of:

* **Science**: New frontiers in drug discovery (gene therapy, siRNA, mRNA), i.e. the products getting commercialized are more complex and require more medical science expertise  
* **Reimbursement**: New payment models (value-based, installment plans for curative interventions)  
* **Delivery**: New routes of administration (in-office, in-hospital, specialty distribution)  
* **Technology**: Digital engagement (preferences for HCPs and patients are driving personalization)

Platforms must enable new commercial and GTM models.

**Technical Challenges** 

* **Support for Multi-Modal Data:** Supporting drug commercialization increasingly relies on evidence generated from semi-structured documentation (eg., EHR notes, patient reported outcomes) and unstructured data (eg., images)   
* **Disconnect between Descriptive and Predictive:** Many commercial brand teams rely on descriptive business intelligence reports; At the same time, data scientists increasingly are building predictive models to inform provider next-best-action: Siloed systems results in duplicative costs, inconsistent business rules, and reduced collaboration between teams   
* **Data Sharing:** Organizations rely on third party data, and exchange of data with partners, which often becomes a bottleneck due to inflexible and proprietary systems.


**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI supports agent frameworks for commercial assistants (egs., for sales reps & MSLs) & next-best-action recommendations  
* **Governance:** Unity Catalog enables end- to-end lineage for Real World Evidence requirements re: reproducibility & regulatory  
* **Streaming & ETL:** Delta Live Tables and Databricks streaming capabilities support digital health applications (eg., continuous glucose)  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** DBSQL and AI/BI support brand analytics & dashboarding (eg., provider segmentation, market share trends)  
* **Data Collaboration:** Marketplace provides quick access to third party data & models (eg., IQVIA, HealthVerity, Definitive)

# Streamline Operations {#streamline-operations}

**Industry Context**  
The healthcare industry is under operational strain. Payers are struggling with new regulatory reporting requirements, and providers are facing unprecedented nursing shortages. Automating healthcare and streamlining operations is no longer a side project: It is perhaps the only way to move the healthcare industry forward. This requires implementing interoperability, automating clinical note review, and improving operating efficiency.

**Business Challenges / Urgency**

* **Regulatory**: CMS has released new regulations around [Interoperability & Patient Access](https://www.cms.gov/priorities/key-initiatives/burden-reduction/interoperability/policies-and-regulations/cms-interoperability-and-patient-access-final-rule-cms-9115-f#:~:text=This%20regulation%20includes%20policies%20which,provider%20or%20between%20two%20payers.), as well as [Interoperability & Prior Authorization](https://www.cms.gov/priorities/key-initiatives/burden-reduction/interoperability/policies-and-regulations/cms-interoperability-and-prior-authorization-final-rule-cms-0057-f) → Data Intelligence can play a critical role in supporting data exchange and accelerating turnaround times  
* **Financial**: Operating margins for many hospitals (particularly rural hospitals and those with a large Medicaid population) are rebounding from 2022, but remain low; Similarly, some insurers are reporting negative operating margins due to unexpected medical and pharmacy costs

**Technology Challenges**

* **Data Silos**: Limited interoperability in current state prevents organizations from aggregating all of their healthcare data (eg., EHR, administrative, claim data) and sharing with partners.  
* **Vast Amounts of Unstructured Data**: Much of the value in healthcare data is in the form of semi-structured (eg., clinical documentation) or unstructured (eg., image) data, requiring capabilities outside of traditional data warehouses.   
* **Sensitive Data / Regulatory & Compliance Standards**: Healthcare data includes identifiable information and is very sensitive, requiring robust data management and governance standards.

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI offers a governed platform to build and deploy models for use cases like payment integrity / fraud detection  
* **Governance:** Row / Column level security in Unity Catalog allows organizations to meet PHI/PII compliance regulations and protect a patient’s identity   
* **Streaming & ETL:** Delta Live Tables unlock real time processing to provide reliable & timely data to solve various clinical and administrative needs  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** DBSQL and AI/BI support business analysts, particularly those in operational reporting capacities  
* **Data Collaboration:** ISV partners support interoperability (eg., Redox) and clinical data abstraction (eg., John Snow Labs)

# Improve Provider Quality & Network Management {#improve-provider-quality-&-network-management}

**Industry Context**  
The shift from fee-for-service to value-based care \- in order to pay providers based on the value they provide to patients rather than the number of services they deliver \- is increasing payment complexity and requiring a new lens of quality measurement. Effective provider network management can help payers identify new providers and services to enhance their networks and meet the evolving needs of their members and patients.

**Business Challenges / Urgency** 

* Government agencies, fueled by initiatives like the Center for Medicare and Medicaid Innovation (CMMI) aiming to shift Medicare beneficiaries into accountable care relationships, are actively promoting value-based care, encouraging wider adoption by healthcare providers.  
* Value-based care requires data intelligence, including the ability to quantify patient outcomes, measure quality of care (and direct patients to high-quality providers), and understand the relationship between cost and quality.  
* Of note, quality ratings (eg., Star ratings) dictate reimbursement for health plans (eg., bonus payments).

**Technical Challenges**

* **Traceability:** Quality measures \- which ultimately dictate payments \- require enhanced transparency and data lineage, particularly as measures change over time and stakeholders need to be informed.  
* **Computational Scale:** Valuable data, such as the Price Transparency Machine Readable Files, are extremely large and challenge most legacy technology systems.  
* **Geospatial Capabilities / Nearest Neighbor Problem:** Aligning patient needs to provider capabilities requires understanding who has access to care from a geospatial point of view. In other words, across an entire patient population, organizations need to quantify whether patients are able to physically access appropriate provider care.

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI offers a governed platform to build and deploy models for use cases like predicting provider performance   
* **Governance:** Unity Catalog enables end- to-end lineage for regulatory requirements around quality measures  
* **Streaming & ETL:** Databricks streaming supports ingest (and parsing) of machine readable files for price transparency  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** Serverless SQL allows organizations to effortlessly scale compute resources dynamically to build benchmarks  
* **Data Collaboration:** Marketplace provides quick access to third party assets including provider reference data (eg., Definitive, Ribbon)

**Common Data Sources: [Production Workloads \[Industry Data Map\]](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1eiN2AgJE4KfV70ISUl5DxjxS-e6z_m3N8NpaSEvdqRs/edit?gid=1776672675#gid=1776672675)**

* Publicly-posted price transparency data by health plans  
* Public APIs for provider directories

# Deliver Better Patient Outcomes & Experience {#deliver-better-patient-outcomes-&-experience}

**Industry Context**  
With a real-time, accurate 360° view of the patient, healthcare organizations can better predict disease, personalize outreach, and improve the delivery of care across all channels, leading to better patient engagement and outcomes. (Note: This is contextualized as member for payers.)

**Business Challenges / Urgency** 

* Despite high-levels of investment, health outcomes in the United States have fallen since the pandemic and lag behind peer countries. Interventions are often reactive and costly.  
* At the same time, patient satisfaction, as measured by the Consumer Assessment of Healthcare Providers and Systems (CAHPS) surveys and other frameworks, is hurting.  
* The healthcare ecosystem as a whole, and healthcare providers and payers in particular, must embrace data \+ AI to deliver better patient outcomes and experience.

**Technical Challenges**

* **Real-Time Insights:** Patient health status is dynamic and requires streaming data velocity, particularly in acute care scenarios.   
* **Fragmented Data / Entity Analytics:** In order to build a true patient 360, healthcare organizations must first establish definitive identities, linking together patient records across disparate data sets and systems.  
* **Productionalizing Machine Learning Models:** Building AND deploying models with robust monitoring & governance capabilities is particularly important in the context of patient care.

**Databricks Technical Advantages**

* **AI:** Mosaic AI supports agent frameworks for patient and member services (eg., chatbots for cost of care)  
* **Governance:** Row / Column level security in Unity Catalog allows organizations to meet PHI/PII compliance regulations and protect a patient’s identity   
* **Streaming & ETL:** Delta Live Tables and Databricks streaming capabilities support digital health applications (eg., continuous glucose)  
* **Data Warehousing & BI:** DBSQL and AI/BI support patient analytics & dashboarding (eg., population health)

Improved Member Retention: Reduced new member attrition by 3.6% by proactively addressing primary care provider assignments. Enhanced Member Experience: Better understood and acted on member needs, improving satisfaction and engagement. Operational Efficiency: Reduced IT operation costs while scaling offerings effectively.
